<h1> Tourist Place </h1>
<hr border="3px" color="red">
<br/>
<p class="intro"> Aina Mahal </p> 

<p class="para"> <b> Aina Mahal </b> is an 18th-Century Palance in <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bhuj" target="_blank"> Bhuj, </a><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gujarat" target="_blank">Gujarat, </a><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/India" target="_blank"> India. </a>It is located next to <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Prag_Mahal">Prag Mahal. </a>It was Built by Rao <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Prag_Mahal"> Lakhpatji </a> in 1761. The Chief Architect  & Designer of Aina Mahal was <b> Ram Singh Malam, </b> who was assisted by local builder community in Construction.
 <ul>
   <li> It was Constructed with <b> Marble Walls </b> adorned with <b> Gold Lace & Glass. </b>
 <ul>
   <li> The Walls of the Palace are of white marble covered with mirrors separated by gilded ornaments with shades of Venetian glass. </li>
 </ul>
</p>
<br/>
<hr border="3px" color="red">
<p class="museum"> Kutch Museum </p>

 <p><b> Kutch Museum </b> in <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bhuj" target="_blank"> Bhuj, </a> is the Oldest Museum of <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gujarat"> Gujarat. </a>It is Located opposite <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hamirsar_Lake"> Hamirsar Lake </a> in <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bhuj"> Bhuj, </a> <a href="//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gujarat"> Gujarat, </a> <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/India"> India. </a>
</p>
 <h2> History </h2>
  <ul>
   <li> Kutch Museum was initialy formed as a part of the School of Arts established by <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Khengarji_III"> Khengarji III</a></li>
   <li> It was founded on 1st July 1877. </li>
   <li> The museum was earlier known as <b> Fergusson Museum </b> </li>
   <li> The Museum, constructed in the Italian Gothic Style </li>
 </ul>
</p>
<br/>
<hr border="3px" color="red">
<br/>

<p class="taj"> Taj Mahal </p>
<p> The Taj Mahal <b> (more often meaning  CROWN of the PALACE). </b> It was commissioned in 1632 by the <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mughal_Empire"> Mughal Empire.</a> and Prince Name <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Shah_Jahan"> Shah Jahan </a> (reigned 1628 - 1658), to house the tomb of his favourite wife, <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mumtaz_Mahal"> Mumtaz Mahal </a>
 <ul>
  <li> The tomb is the centrepience of a 17-hactor (42 Acer) complex.
 <ul>
   <li> Includes a <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mosque"> Mosque </a> and a Guest House.</li>
 </ul>
 <ul>
   <li> Gardens bounded on three side by <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Battlement"> Crenellated Wall </a></li>
 </ul>
</p>
<p>
  <ol>
   <li>  It's entirety in 1653 at a cost estimated at the time to be around 32 million rupees, which in 2015 would be approximately 52.8 billion rupees (US $827 million).</li>
   <li> The construction project employed some 20,000 artisans under the guidance of a board of architects led by the court architect to the emperor, <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ustad_Ahmad_Lahori"> Ustad Ahmad Lahori </a></li>
   </ol>
 </p>
